So, so...incredibly bummed at the prospects of a 50-person Zoom class.
You're an aspiring investor, CEO,  founder,  programmer,  writer and so on.
You want to be the best.
So why aren't you copying the best?
I hear the term 'imposter syndrome' used quite frequently among those entering tech.
Coming from a social science background, I can empathize.
Learning to program is difficult.
Especially when you come from a non-technical background and are self-taught.
There is a remedy ð§ª ð  and it applies to learning *anything* seemingly difficult:
It's one thing to practice and continually work at our craft.
It's another thing to be deliberate about it.
Deliberate practice.
The 10,000 hours rule.
You may have heard it popularized by Malcolm Gladwell.

Here's how I learned about deliberate practice from a comedian and how you can incorporate it into your own practiceð

#deliberatepractice

Think back to when you started learning a new thing, did you wonder:

"How long will this take?"

â³

That question has crossed my mind countless times over the years in my coding/data science journey.
But time is a flawed marker of progress.
Here are some better alternatives for anyone learning a new *anything* :)
I think primary and secondary education (heck even college/grad schools) should try to introduce and reinforce the **Pareto Principle**.
What's the **80/20** of any given situation?
What's the highest leverage activity I can do, right now?
Whether you're in business, an investor, a student or an aspiring data person, this can simplify your path.

I can't believe my kids are nearing 14th months!
Time flies and you can never get it back (that's what I keep reminding myself).

I take them on evening walks, while they're still around 10kg, but the window is closing ð They are beginning to babble, make incoherent sounds and occasionally say something that resembles language - and everyone around us is reading it into it.
Mommy thinks they're saying "mommy", grandmas and aunties are biased in the other direction.

Personally, I think my son's first words will be a version of, "hey google, play jazz" because we say that everyday ð

Marvin is predisposed to being fearless, while my daughter Milin is more cautious.
Milin started walking faster but Marvin has caught up and is now climbing ð¬ They both know how to get attention and are not shy about using their voices.
We've set up a Montessori station, but this is an area where theory and practice diverge.
We've read the book, taken some workshops, and yet in the face of a 14 month old babies - theory goes out the window.
We'll take it day-by-day.
If anyone else has tried to take development into their own hands, do share your experiences.
On the work front, my data science journey continues.

It started with a specific tool (R) and area of focus (people analytics), but i'm realizing this field favors the multi-lingual (hence i'm working on Python) and I don't wanna be pegged to a specific org function, like HR.
I just finished teaching introduction to R and exploratory data visualization and will open-source my materials soon.

More details on that front here: http://getwyze.com/my-data-journey-to-yours-a-variety-of-data-flavors/

Until next time.

Got 2020 fatigue?
Let's take a trip down memory lane to everyone fav icon 90's sitcom.
Friends generally got 20 - 30 million views every episode for 10 years.
But for two episodes in season 2, viewership jumped to 50+ million views credit to guest starts Julia Roberts and Jean-Claude Van Damme.
After the first season, the show runners must've known they had something special, so it was smart to book high profile actors to give the show a boost.
Heat maps are aesthetically more interesting to look at when there's range restriction in the data, we see much more diversity in color for IMDB ratings (than viewership).
When filtering for episodes with the highest ratings AND viewership, we get the seminal episodes in the show's history.
These episodes, for the most part, advance the Ross/Rachel and Monica/Chandler story arc that form the backbone of the series.
Take away these 7 episodes and we get a completely different show.
Credit to the writer for imbuing the characters with a full range of emotions.
While not part of the main plot, Joey and Phoebe carry their fair share of the emotional work.

This year, they partnered with Doctors Without Borders, a medical humanitarian organization that delivers emergency aid to people affected by conflict, epidemics and natural disasters.

Hello GSSE fam,

Just wanted to share a prototype I've been working on with my medical doctor friend.
It's a dashboard designed to help hospitals manage important resource during a pandemic outbreak.
Although we're on a pretty good trajectory in Thailand, one can never be too careful - and there's a possibility of a second or third wave of infections.
So this dashboard can be used to see how various hospitals have to manage their staff, space and supplies, *efficiently* so they can service new patients.
If anyone reading this knows of medical doctors or hospital administrators, please feel free to share as it's a work-in-progress and we're thirsty for feedback :) ð

Excited to share a prototype of a hospital dashboard i've been working with my good friend @[9434573:2048:Timothy Decha-Umphai] to create to help small-medium sized hospitals prepare *just in case* there's a second or third wave of #covid19 infections (not to mention the uncertainty around this virus).
This is a tool to help visualize some resources a hospital ð¥ needs to manage in case of a surge in patients.
To minimize complexity, we focus on two primary types of data "stock" (how many supplies, staff and beds does the hospital have?)
and "flow" data (how efficiently are patients being moved throughout the system?).
As a medical doctor whose worked in hospitalist and in hospital administration, @[9434573:2048:Timothy Decha-Umphai] 's input has been invaluable.
In addition, we've tried to incorporate literature on pandemic planning.
It's certainly been educational for me to learn about how hospitals must manage their resources during these challenging times.

ð¢This is definitely a Work-in-Progress, so If you know any medical doctorsð©âð¬ð¨âð¬, hospital administrators, please share, we'd love to get some feedback and engagement to see if it's worth developing further.

ð

This dashboard is made with R, Shiny and some Javascript.

You can play with the Live App here ðð²https://paulapivat.shinyapps.io/dashboard_app/

We've written an explainer here detailing various scenarios where hospital capacity becomes strained here ðð§ http://getwyze.com/hospital-dashboard-prototype-surge-capacity-scenarios/

Do I know any Tour de France fans?

Here's a plot of how far each of the winners had to ride; from 1903 - 2019.
On a single tour basis, Lucien Buysse had to work the hardest for his win logging 5745 kmð¥µ back in 1926.
For context, that's cycling from Bangkok to Chiangmai and back, 4 times!
Lance Armstrong won the event 7 consecutive times (the most in history), but each of his tours were less than 4000 km...still impressive, scandal notwithstanding.

Other names worth highlighting: Jacques Anquetil (5x winner, back in the 60's); Eddy Merckx (5x winner, early 70's); Miguel Indurain (5x winner, early 90's); Bernard Hinault (5x, late 70's) and, more recently, Chris Froome (4x, 2013 - 2017).

55 days to go from 0 -> 100

At that rate, we should be at 10,000 in two days(!)
(Apr 6th), but that's not likely to happen given recent trends.

Some possibilities:

1.

More cases will emerge with more testing (we're still early)
2.

Under reporting of cases (information suppression)
3.

A case for *cautious* optimism

Are we bending the curve?

*last update: April 3rd, 2020*

This upcoming week is important, here's a score card I use to see how we're doing against #COVID19.

These only reflect reported confirmed cases (i've heard anecdotally of people *not* reporting positive cases for fear of social stigma or losing face)

From March 24 - 27th, we had relatively "slow" growth in new cases (green color).
Yesterday and Today, the growth has picked up (red) - not good.
At this pace, it wouldn't surprised me if we reach 2500 by *this* Wednesday.
Let's hope it doesn't get there.
My friend asked me what to expect in the next several weeks.
Very difficult to answer given so many uncertainties.
I want avoid prediction, so i'll lay out some scenarios: Good, Bad, Worse, Worst.
Good scenario: IF we have 2500 confirmed cases on April 1st, it would be a good sign if we have 3500 by April 7th.
This would suggest incremental growth.
Bad: 7000 by April 7th.
More than doubled in a week's time.
Worse: 15000 by April 7th.
Worst: 26000 by April 7th.
Our Tests Per Confirmed Case has been dropping steadily in March suggesting that there are more new cases than new tests.
Wishlist: More aggressive testing.
The Govt has set up check points for temperature checks.
My wish is that they interrogate people with high temperature and find out who they've been in contact with in the last 7-10 days and then test *those people*.

Happy birthday Peter!
Wishing you and your family well during this crazy time!
Need a break from covid19.
Did a quick visual of brain-trauma injuries.
You'd think that Assault or Motor Vehicle related injuries would dominate.
As contributors to brain trauma, they peak btwn 15-24 yrs (when we feel like we'd live forever).
But the biggest threat is "unintentionally falling" ð ð¤ It's the largest source of brain trauma throughout our lives and increases as we age.
On a related note, "The Fall Matrix".
Concept is simple: if we train our bodies to get down and up off the floor, we will be using muscle and movement patterns that keep our bodies functional as we age.

I want to update the dashboard, now that I have updated information.

https://paulapivat.shinyapps.io/covidgrowth/

Because Testing is emerging as a strategic tool against #covid19,
I've added Tests Per One Million People to allow cross-country comparisons.
For context, S.Korea performed 6148 tests per one million people to date (United States 313, Italy 3,498 to date respectively).

Data source: https://ourworldindata.org/covid-testing

For Thailand, we are currently at 169 tests per one million which *could* mean we're later in the game or have yet to ramp up our testing (the Ministry of Public Health has officially stated that our testing capacity is at 10,000 tests per day in Bangkok; provincial areas combined also at 10,000 tests per day).
I've also added Tests Per Confirmed Cases.
Some countries have tested aggressively (and proactively), so you'd expect this number to be higher, while other countries have been more reactive.
For context, Italy is at approx 3.5 tests per case, US at 7 tests per case, Thailand at 14.28 tests per case, S.Korea at 35 tests per case and Taiwan at 126 tests per case.
I think this number gives us a sense of how aggressive we are in testing.
I'd want to see this number to go up.

Data source: https://ourworldindata.org/covid-testing

Finally, Growth Factor (green) has been less than 1.15 for two consecutive days, which means there is growth, but not at an accelerated pace (for now) and our Healthcare infrastructure has some time to get ready (we want to avoid see it go to red for consecutive days).

****

As major parts of the city shut down and we practice social distancing, many of us fortunate to be able to work from home, are beginning to question:

- how long will we have to stay home and practice social distancing?
- how long will schools, entertainment venues shut down?
- how long until small businesses run out of cashflow?
- how long before the economy goes into a deep recession?
No one knows for sure.
At this point, there are more questions than answers because thereâs not enough data to reliably answer much.
What i think we *can* do is look at the data that is available to us.
To that end, Iâd like to focus on numbers that donât get as much attention from the media.
To be sure, there are lots of visualizations, graphics and dashboard for tracking COVID-19, so I wanted to focus on one  important aspect: itâs growth.
I made a dashboard tracking two types of growth - the familiar day-to-day growth rate in total confirmed cases and Growth Factor.

(Currently focused on Thailand, but hoping to add US/Italy/S.Korea/Singapore for comparison)

See here: https://paulapivat.shinyapps.io/covidgrowth/ 

This should give us some sense for where we are in the growth curve of this virus.
If the growth factor is *consistently* between 1.15 - 1.25 or higher, it means weâll see a doubling in our total confirmed cases in about 5 days.

Read more here: http://getwyze.com/growth-factor/

If after a period of fast growth, the number gets down to about 1.0, we might be at an inflection point where we might have peaked.
Thereâs a lot of uncertainty and these are fundamentally lagging indicators (so weâre not doing any forecasting here).
In creating this dashboard, I ran into some interesting data challenges, inconsistencies and availability.

I wrote about those challenges and my temporary solution here: http://getwyze.com/tracking-covid-19-growth/

Iâll be updating this dashboard manually everyday as new numbers become available.

Be safe and happy social distancing,

Hey all,

I'd like to share the reasoning behind my concern with #COVID19 with some data/visualizations.
In short, the exponential growth pattern of across multiple countries is alarming.
We've been relatively lucky to have experienced incremental growth, to date, but I fear that could change for the worse and the healthcare infrastructure in this country will be tested.
Thai numbers are assuming accurate reporting, accurate data.
As a university, i'm hoping we consider moving to online/remote learning as soon as possible.
Personally speaking, I don't think this is one of those "wait and see" situations.
At the end of the post, I share resources for individuals and organizational leaders.
Stay safe everyone.
Practice social distancing (spend time with family, at home).
Wash your hands.

I'm not sensing a sufficient level of urgency around me regarding  COVID-19, so I'm sharing some data and visualizations, hoping to highlight an under-reported aspect of the coronavirus.
Those who have been following the news are aware of the numbers - confirmed cases, deaths and recovered - but these static numbers bury the lead of the story, in my view.
The important thing to grasp is the growth rate.
Not incremental growth, but exponential growth.
We tend to think linearly and that's a mistake in this situation.
We feel for Italy and we think maybe it's just because they weren't prepared.
But the growth rates displayed in Italy are present in many other countries.
I think it would be foolish to think "oh that's won't happen in my country".
I think we need to move to remote work/classes, practice social distancing immediately, and frankly, postpone weddings, social gatherings, conferences, meetups etc.
Anything else is flirting with risk.
Please read on.
At the end of the post I have a list of resources for individuals and organizational leaders.

Stay safe, wash your hands and spend time with your family (at home)ð

How has Thailand ð¹ð­ changed over the last 20 years?
One way of answering that question is to examine data on the Average Monthly Household Income for all provinces.
This was a super fun project and i'm excited for how this one turned out.
Thankful ð for data.go.th, DGA Thailand and the National Statistics Office for making publicly available these longitudinal data sets.

ðOverall trendsð: 

Largest growth in average household income from Chaiyaphum down to the Eastern seaboard, and further down south (Chumphon, Surat Thani, Phangnga and Krabi).
Surprisingly, Chiang Mai and Chiang Rai are two among several provinces that experienced the least growth.

For 3rd or 4th year senior students who are planning their next move after graduation, you might be interested in applying for Scholarships for graduate studies at some point.
Data.go.th has made available their Thai Government Scholarship raw data by type and country (over many years; last updated Jan 2018).

Here's the data visualized in a Treemap so you can see which Ministry has given out the most scholarships (Ministry of Science & Technology), which scholarships favor studies in specific countries (e.g., if you wanted to study in Japan specifically, the ODOS - One District One Scholarship - is a good bet).

Or even which scholarship has been most selective; there are two scholarships that are even more selective than the prestigious KING's scholarship (MOPH - Ministry of Public Health & MFA - Ministry of Foreign Affairs).

Full post: http://getwyze.com/a-treemap-of-government-scholarships-given-in-thailand-%f0%9f%87%b9%f0%9f%87%ad/

"There are 82-game players, and then there are 16-game players" - Draymond Green

Well now that we're past the All-Star break, NBA fans are gearing up for the second sweetest words in the sport: Playoff Basketball.
Casual basketball fans will know that as there's a *qualitative* difference between the regular season and the playoffs.
The game slows down, teams are more strategic, defenses get tighter and the pressure is intensified.
But can we quantitatively show this?
In this post, we examine Giannis Antetokounmpo's impact on his team's dominance rating.
Specifically, we use multiple regression to find out just how much Giannis' impact differs between the regular season and the playoffs.
We code the NBA season as a categorical variable with two levels - regular vs playoffs - to see if Giannis is an 82-game player or a 16-game player.

Growing up we all wanted to me like Michael Jordan and we never cared how "efficient" he was.
Well times have changed.
The sports analytics movement started in baseball and quickly infiltrated front offices across the NBA.
Now we don't just want our superstars to score 60+ points, we want to know that they did it with fewer shots (and with many 3's).

In this post, we'll examine one of the more popular individual performance metric, the Player Efficiency Rating (created by John Hollinger, and whether its associated with the Team's dominance (ELO rating).
Specifically, we're looking at Giannis' PER (2018-19 season) and it's relationship to the Buck's ELO rating.
More importantly, we're using simple linear regression.

When it comes to understanding your favorite blockchain protocol, economics and game theory turn out to be invaluable tools.
Despite the ethos of decentralization, the underlying market structure of certain protocols may be more akin to "winner take all" (or at least a group of winners colluding).
Blockchain markets may be more similar to a few large Telecom companies (think AIS, DTAC, TRUE) dominating a market than we initially thought.
Left uncheck, we may see clear market dominance of certain mining pools (like the FANG stocks of blockchain mining).
When evaluating certain projects, it may be important to see if the designers are actively exploring ways to discourage (or at least check) oligopolistic tendencies.

Been thinking about governance lately.
Effective governance gives us confidence that the organization we work for has not only our best interests at heart, but customers, stakeholders and wider community that we serve.
Without good governance, you have no choice but to hope that your leader is virtuous (and competent), or a benevolent dictator.
Worst case scenario, in cases where leaders lack virtue & competence, effective governance (checks and balances, a strong board) saves people from themselves.

For public infrastructure networks (i.e., blockchains) the importance of governance is magnified 100X because there is no person to be single point of failure (ð) and, on the flip side, no person to be accountable for in case something happens to public assets (ð­).
In this post, I borrow from the exciting multi-disciplinary field of Collective Intelligence to exam how the Ethereum network could tackle some of its governance challenges.

: this workshop will explore innovation leadership by diving deep into tactical methods from the THNK School of Creative Leadership and the fields of Human-Centered Design Tools and Organizational Design Frameworks.

10 Biggest learning from a semester of teaching: 1.
Classroom management may be just as important, if not more, than the actual 'content', 2.
Less content may result in more learning (which kind of contradicts the next point), 3.
When i wonder "is this too much for the students?"
- - it's probably just right, 4.
Structured team-based work is great; teams composed of friends may not be so great, 5.
Students crave feedback, 6.
Students want a mix of imposed structure and choice, 7.
Student-centered and project-based learning works (particularly for exposure to social issues) - -but its not always obvious, 8.
Lectures should be kept to 15 mins max, 9.
It's important to swing from teacher-as-expert to teacher-as-facilitator/coach (and occasionally teacher-as-disciplinarian), 10.

It's my understanding that when you signed up for facebook, you're essentially renting cyber-land.
Anything you build on that land (post) belongs to facebook (the landlord).
If it's personal pictures in which you have no intention of commercializing - no harm no foul, right?

[assuming that if privacy was your main concern, you wouldn't be posting in the first place]

But if you have any content you wish to benefit from in the future (i.e., commercialize, brand, sell), it's probably a good idea to get your own website (that means your facebook page shouldn't be your only online presence).
Discussion welcomed.
